# Rules

- No emojis e.g. 😀 of any kind
- No semicolons e.g. ; in prose (code is exempt)
- Always use plain ASCII no Unicode. Eg no em/en dash.

# Agent memory

Lessons that should persist across sessions live in the `memory` skill. Read that skill before similar work; do not run bare `memory` or `memory view` for context.

## When to add

Record cross-session lessons: recurring pitfalls, non-obvious conventions, or fixes that took real investigation. Do not use memory for one-off task notes or incident logs.

## How to add

Use the `memory` CLI:

```
memory add <id> <one-line lesson> [--detail [content...]]
```

- `<id>`: kebab-case, at most 4 hyphen-separated words (e.g. `checkout-redis`)
- Lesson: one line, max 120 characters; quote the sentence if the shell would split it
- `--detail` writes reference markdown to `references/<id>.md` (arguments or stdin); use when the lesson needs more than one line
- `hasDetails` in `entries.json` is set when reference content exists; the skill bullet gets a suffix pointing agents at the reference file

Example:

```
memory add checkout-redis "Checkout bugs often involve stale Redis entries." --detail "Keys persist after session merge until TTL expires."
```

Duplicate ids are rejected. The CLI regenerates the `memory` skill from `entries.json`.

## Human-only commands

Do not run bare `memory`. It opens an interactive browser for humans in a TTY (Up/Down, Enter for rendered details, `x` to remove). When `CURSOR_AGENT` is set, bare `memory` prints CLI help instead.

`memory view <id>` prints raw markdown for one entry. When `CURSOR_AGENT` is set, it prints only: "Agents should read the memory skill instead of this command."

Agents should read the `memory` skill and `references/<id>.md` directly instead.

